immediately deep to the nipple (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the discharge?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic cystic mastitis","Duct ectasia","Duct papilloma","Duct carcinoma in-situ","Paget disease of the nipple"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESpontaneous, unilateral nipple discharge suggests a pathological cause. Whilst duct papilloma is the commonest cause of a pathological nipple discharge, the material is usually clear or bloody. Similarly, the discharge in duct carcinoma in-situ is often either clear or bloody. In this case, the discharge is a greenish colour and the underlying cause is more likely to be \u003Cstrong\u003Educt ectasia\u003C/strong\u003E. This is also supported by her age. The absence of breast tenderness or swelling makes mastitis less likely. Paget\u2019s disease of the nipple is rare and typically features visible nipple changes such as scaling or retraction and not discharge. Regardless, tissue diagnosis is important for all pathological discharge to exclude carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most types of nipple discharge have benign origins."],"references":["Mazzarello S, Arnaout A. Nipple discharge.\u00a0CMAJ. 2015;187(8):599. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25733736/","Brennan M, Houssami N, French J. Management of benign breast conditions. Australial Family Physician. 2005;34(5):353-355. Available at: www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/1a72c8ea-0f45-4a3d-9f61-3e30ccde65e3/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"412"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21141"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21141"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://ap